SIMPLE: housing
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Housing
<hw>Hous"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>House</er>.
In some of its senses this word has been confused with the following
word.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of putting or receiving under
shelter; the state of dwelling in a habitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which shelters or covers; houses, taken
collectively.</def> <rj><au>Fabyan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The space taken out
of one solid, to admit the insertion of part of another, as the end of
one timber in the side of another.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A niche for a
statue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A frame or support for holding
something in place, such as a piece of machinery, journal boxes,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>That portion of a
mast or bowsprit which is beneath the deck or within the vessel.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A covering or protection, as an awning over the deck
of a ship when laid up.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A houseline. See
<er>Houseline</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Housing</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Housing
<hw>Hous"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Houss</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A cover or cloth for a horse's saddle, as an ornamental
or military appendage; a saddlecloth; a horse cloth; in plural,
trappings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An appendage to the hames or collar of a
harness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>housings</ent>⟦br⟧
